[Unknown]: Thank you.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Ruben, before we sort of get to the topic at hand, tell me a little bit about the IDFC Institute. What does it do?

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:23.000
[Guest 2]: So, I'd say broadly speaking, it's an institute that was set up as a sort of think-do tank. And the reason we say think-do tank is because most think tanks and academic institutions tend to restrict itself to asking what questions and why questions without getting into the how of it.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:30.000
[Guest 2]: And most public policy interventions actually get stuck on the how of it because the how is where political economy gets involved.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:43.000
[Guest 2]: So, we're actually involved in what we sort of broadly sort of define as ideate, innovate, implement, institutionalize. Those are the four stages of public policy as we see it.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:52.000
[Guest 2]: So, we obviously have some deep sectoral knowledge as well, but I think you can actually apply this principle no matter what realm of public policy you look at.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
[Guest 2]: So, that's broadly speaking the remit of what we do.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:04.000
[Amit Varma]: So, essentially you go in there saying not just that we're going to find out what policy works and should be implemented, but also what policy can practically be carried out and pushed through theâ€¦

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:10.000
[Guest 2]: That's right. Because ultimately in public policy, if you aren't capable of implementing it, what's the point?

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.000
[Guest 2]: Right. And so, unlike other think tanks, you actually want to make a difference.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:27.000
[Guest 2]: I think most think tanks would like to make a difference. I think the problem is that in general people who are technically trained, therefore have a bias towards thinking that a solution is also technical.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
[Guest 2]: Right. Keep in mind, I had exactly the same bias, right?

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:38.000
[Guest 2]: So, when you look at a problem closely enough that you realize that the technical piece is important, obviously you can't do anything without the idea in the first place.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:46.000
[Guest 2]: But once you have that, and specifically in public policy, you've got to see it through. You can't leave that to someone else.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And what are the sort of areas in which, you know, IDFC has expertise where you try to make a difference?

00:04:51.000 --> 00:05:02.000
[Guest 2]: Yeah, so I'd say broadly speaking, so beyond the, what we described as sort of state capability, governance, all of that, which are more sort of horizontal generic knowledge.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:10.000
[Guest 2]: I think the specialized knowledge is across three verticals, which is urbanization, the reform of the welfare state, and the criminal justice system.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
[Guest 2]: Those are broadly the three areas where we have deep expertise.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. And, and Pritika, you've done a master's in city planning from MIT. So, can I ask how you got to that? Like, you know, how did you begin to look at cities differently once you actually did your courses and so on?

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:35.000
[Guest 1]: That's a great question. So my undergrad was in development economics. And so I think I started with an interest in development questions.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:39.000
[Guest 1]: And then I worked in economic consulting for a while, so completely different.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:49.000
[Guest 1]: And then when I was going back to graduate school and had conversations with my advisors, I think the way I thought about cities was the location for development.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:06:02.000
[Guest 1]: Right. And so, I mean, the reason I was interested in cities is a very multidisciplinary topic. But I think also in the way in which we think about city planning, we have to be prepared to think about economic development.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:07.000
[Guest 1]: And then, you know, physical planning, transport planning, and a whole host of other things.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Just the sort of term city planning seems to denote a top down way of thinking. And obviously, you've done economics before this, so you understand how market works. And, you know, cities also are another form of spontaneous order.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Did that make a difference in how you looked at city planning? And who are the sort of the people who influence the way you look at city planning?

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:43.000
[Guest 1]: So no question. In fact, I was one of the few people that came from a fairly solid economics background, and I wasn't afraid of our urban economic classes. And I think what ends up happening is you have generations of planners that think of cities as sort of a top down.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:55.000
[Guest 1]: So not only take a top down approach to cities, but also think of markets as something you can plan and you can't. And so I think that's definitely, you know, something that I took away from the program.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:06.000
[Guest 1]: The two people I think that influenced me the most is Alain Berto, who's at NYU and Vimal Patel, who's done an incredible job of planning and economics in India.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:07.000
[Guest 1]: And who's joining you guys in ideas.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:08.000
[Guest 1]: Yes, who's joining us as a fellow.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And in general, Ruben, you wrote a piece recently with Robert Maga where, you know, I'll quote from that where you guys say,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:30.000
[Amit Varma]: cities, not nation states are the dominant force of human civilization in the 21st century, humanity transition from a rural to a primarily urban species, Homo Urbanus at breathtaking speed in the early 1800s, less than 3% of the world's population lived in cities.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:43.000
[Amit Varma]: Today, more than half the global population is urban and by 2050, the proportion will rise to three quarters. Stop quote. Why has this move towards urbanism happened? And what are the sort of challenges that then holds?

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:51.000
[Guest 2]: So, yeah, so I think what cities really do is they provide you economies of scale and economies of agglomeration.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:59.000
[Guest 2]: And those two sets of economies basically allow you to sort of build job markets, labor markets specifically.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:09.000
[Guest 2]: And I think the reason why people generally move to cities, and I think this is perhaps sort of Alain Berto's great contribution is to define cities as labor markets.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:20.000
[Guest 2]: And these are not the creatures of an architect's imagination, so to speak, right? I mean, so yes, people like us perhaps have the luxury of saying, you know, we live in Mumbai for X or Y reason.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:28.000
[Guest 2]: But the primary reason why most people who have moved to Bombay have moved here is purely to find a job. And that's true of most cities around the world.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:34.000
[Guest 2]: So, in effect, the cities are just labor markets. So, you effectively move to where the jobs are.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:43.000
[Guest 2]: Equally, there's another transitional phase that has happened over the last 200 years, which is the transition towards through industrialization through to service economies, right?

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:49.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, so we were primarily an agricultural society, no matter where in the world you look. And then you have industrial society.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:54.000
[Guest 2]: So, surplus labor comes out of agriculture. They need to be employed somewhere. That's the industrialization process.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:01.000
[Guest 2]: And then as productivity goes up in the industrial sector, you start moving into the service sector, right? So, that's the process by which it happens.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:07.000
[Guest 2]: So, the question is, what is the location of industrialization and what is the location of the service economy?

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:12.000
[Guest 2]: And those generally tend to be cities because you actually start agglomerating people.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:19.000
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, it's natural that, you know, people want to be in as large economic networks as possible. So, they come to cities and it gets denser and denser.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.000
[Guest 2]: Yeah. And does it at some levelâ€¦

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.000
[Guest 2]: So, again, from a job market perspective, it also allows you to shift jobs.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.000
[Guest 2]: Yeah. Right. I mean, so the larger the market, the more opportunities there are.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
[Guest 2]: Division of labor, specialization, blah, blah, all of that.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:36.000
[Amit Varma]: And does that in some senses conflict with how a nation state sees itself?

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:42.000
[Amit Varma]: So, for example, here you have, say, the city of Mumbai, where people are coming because of the economic networks here.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.000
[Amit Varma]: There are all kinds of jobs, no matter what your skills are, you can specialize and so on and so forth.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:53.000
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, you have a lot of regulations which put restraints on this kind of movement and cohabiting together.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:10:00.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, we were talking about FSI before this episode and I've done an episode on that earlier with Alex Tabarrok while he was with you guys in Mumbai.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:09.000
[Amit Varma]: So, is that a conflict which somehow needs to be sorted out between governance and the natural spontaneous order which brings people to cities?

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:14.000
[Guest 1]: So, as the city's economic base evolves, the built form needs to evolve as well.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
[Guest 1]: So, I think the example we were discussing is the meatpacking district in New York.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:26.000
[Guest 1]: So, you know, when it's a manufacturing or, you know, hub, you need a very different built form than when it's a services hub.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:34.000
[Guest 1]: So, allowing for higher FSI as your economic base changes, putting in more mass public transit as you have people,

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:38.000
[Guest 1]: more people coming to work versus people being able to drive in is very important.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:45.000
[Guest 1]: And so I think when we don't allow planning to evolve, we end up stifling the economic base of our cities.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:52.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. And just for my listeners who might not be familiar with the term, FSI basically means how high you're allowed to build.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Nuts and bolts, that's what it comes down to. I had an episode on this with Alex Tabarrok, which will be linked from this episode page,

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:03.000
[Amit Varma]: which had the title of Reclaim the Sky, where Alex eloquently said that why should we reclaim the sea?

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, Mumbai can't, you know, expand much in terms of its geography.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:11.000
[Amit Varma]: We should reclaim the sky and kind of expand upwards.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:18.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's just sort of one example of the kind of regulations which hamper the natural movements of cities.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:25.000
[Amit Varma]: But to this, critics would say that you can't just have anarchy and people going wherever and you need to somehow control all of that.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
[Amit Varma]: How do you respond to that?

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:37.000
[Guest 1]: So you do. You cannot have. So FSI, floor space index, is basically a ratio that defines how much floor space you can build as a ratio of your plot area.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:43.000
[Guest 1]: So it's a technical term and it takes into account things like the location of the plot.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:47.000
[Guest 1]: It could take into account the soil quality, accessibility.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:56.000
[Guest 1]: So at a given point in time, a certain plot may have certain features and so can only support, you know, so many people.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:01.000
[Guest 1]: What we forget is that the carrying capacity of a plot can be enhanced.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:09.000
[Guest 1]: So if an area is serviced by a road, for instance, instead of the road, you can put in place BRT or you can put in a metro.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.000
[Guest 1]: And so that same plot becomes accessible to so many more people.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:21.000
[Guest 1]: Now, there is a cap on how much a given plot can take, but then it's for planners to tweak those over time.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:28.000
[Guest 1]: And so I completely understand why people balk at, you know, higher FSI and lower PRL,

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:34.000
[Guest 1]: because all you think is I'm constantly stuck in a traffic jam. It's hard to walk or to get anywhere.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
[Guest 1]: You know, how are we going to have taller buildings with the given transit?

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:45.000
[Guest 1]: And I think what's key that city governments do is enhance carrying capacity at the same time that they allow the area to densify.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:51.000
[Guest 1]: The other thing that often gets conflated is density of people and density of space.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:59.000
[Guest 1]: So if you look at the older parts of Bombay, they were built, you know, to a certain height as the areas became more desirable.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:04.000
[Guest 1]: The amount of built space didn't change. But because more people wanted to live there,

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:09.000
[Guest 1]: they just subdivided and you had more people living in the same amount of space.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:17.000
[Guest 1]: If you instead recognize that there is demand for an area, allow the buildings to redevelop, you know, taller, more space,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
[Guest 1]: you will actually get the same number of people in slightly more space.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
[Guest 1]: It, you know, has implications for affordability as well.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:34.000
[Guest 1]: If you think of land prices as a constraint, the best way to sort of lessen that constraint is to divide the land plot by larger number of units.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:41.000
[Guest 1]: And so I think the sort of reflexive response to FSI doesn't take into account a large number of these factors.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:47.000
[Guest 2]: I think there's also an interesting sort of underlying question here, which sits at the sort of heart of public policy,

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:51.000
[Guest 2]: which is how much regulation is enough regulation? Right.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:56.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, and the fact is, none of us really know how much regulation is enough regulation.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
[Guest 2]: Or even how much regulation is too much regulation.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:06.000
[Guest 2]: It's too much regulation. Right. So I think in the urban context, I think the sort of gold standard is the Commissioner's plan for New York City.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:14.000
[Guest 2]: That was really a thought experiment that was carried out in 1811, where the state government of New York basically commissioned,

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:19.000
[Guest 2]: Governor Morris basically commissioned these three people to do a thought exercise.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:26.000
[Guest 2]: And the scenario they were planning was, so New York at that point has, is mostly concentrated in the tip of New York, around Wall Street.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
[Guest 2]: And it has approximately 25,000 people.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:38.000
[Guest 2]: So they basically said, let's do a 200 year planning exercise where the population of the city will actually go from 25,000 to a million.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:45.000
[Guest 2]: Now, let's plan for it. This plan is the street grid of New York. Right.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:54.000
[Guest 2]: So keep in mind that nothing's built. It's just a statutory map that's basically been put into place, which says, if New York grows,

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:02.000
[Guest 2]: if the economic activity in New York goes up and therefore people move here, etc. This is the way the city will actually grow.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:08.000
[Guest 2]: So if you look at the underlying base map, for instance, you won't see Central Park, but Central Park is like a Lego block.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
[Guest 2]: It's literally been sort of placed on top of the street grid.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:17.000
[Guest 2]: So the width of the roads, the size of all of this was determined in 1811.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:24.000
[Guest 2]: But they didn't then go on to basically say, you will have X kind of industry here and Y kind of industry there.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:29.000
[Guest 2]: They said nothing of the sort. They simply said, if the city grows, here's how the city will grow.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:34.000
[Guest 2]: And there's an underlying street grid that basically allows for this growth of the city.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:39.000
[Guest 2]: And funnily enough, like, you know, some of the old Indian cities are actually built on street grids.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:42.000
[Amit Varma]: But were they planned or did they just happen to come up with street grids?

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
[Guest 2]: Yeah, they were planned. They were planned. Because I mean, they're literally perpendicular.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:49.000
[Guest 2]: So if you go to old city of Jaipur, you will see it. There's a grid exactly like the New York grid.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:54.000
[Amit Varma]: So how much should you plan? Like, okay, at the level of the street grid, you just pointed out, it makes sense.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
[Amit Varma]: What is too much? Where do you draw that line?

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:03.000
[Guest 2]: I think too much is the point at which you become too static and don't allow for dynamism.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:08.000
[Guest 2]: So it's a little bit like what Pritika was pointing earlier, which is things keep changing. Right?

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:14.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, so the economic profile of a city moves. So New York used to be in garments, and then garments just disappeared.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:19.000
[Guest 2]: You need to allow the city to actually move from one industry to the other.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:28.000
[Guest 2]: So anything that prevents the dynamism involved in the ability of a city to adapt to changing conditions, to me is too much regulation.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:29.000
[Guest 2]: Such as?

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:37.000
[Guest 2]: So let's take the FSI of Bombay. Right? Just keeping a strict 1.3 all over the city of Bombay, to me, it's just, it's a static.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Well, other big cities are 15 to 30 and so on.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:44.000
[Guest 2]: But again, it's very granular. Right? I mean, so when you say 25 in Singapore, it's not all of Singapore.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
[Guest 2]: It's the CBD of Singapore, the central business district of Singapore that has 25.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.000
[Guest 2]: So you just need granular planning, right?

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:57.000
[Guest 2]: Which then allows for the city to evolve based on how the market dynamics work.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:01.000
[Guest 2]: So it's not like I am suggesting that this is the only way that the city will evolve.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
[Guest 2]: I'm saying, I don't know.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:12.000
[Guest 2]: So let's actually have a system that takes into account ignorance and you're just as ignorant as I am as to where the city goes.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:22.000
[Amit Varma]: So what you just pointed out about New York was in a sense, it feels very unusual to me because it's these guys planning way ahead of time before there's even really a city there.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:27.000
[Amit Varma]: But typically how city planning happens, it would be fairly reactive. Right?

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Because otherwise, what's the impetus for planning?

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:34.000
[Guest 2]: So I'm not entirely sure that is the case because you've got any number of examples of cities that are built on a grid.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:44.000
[Guest 2]: So if you actually look at the United States as a whole, I mean, there is the Jeffersonian grid, which is, you know, west of the Mississippi, the entire United States is on a grid.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:51.000
[Guest 2]: And so you just need to go on Google Maps and like zoom into a place like Omaha in Nebraska and you'll see it's on a grid.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:54.000
[Guest 2]: And this is all stuff that was done ages ago.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
[Guest 2]: So Barcelona is on a grid.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, there's any number of cities globally that are on a grid.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:08.000
[Guest 2]: I think a lot of this really comes from if your starting point is that cities matter and we need to plan for it, as opposed to this is a terrible thing.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
[Guest 2]: You know, let's try to prevent people from coming in.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
[Guest 2]: I think your starting point matters.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:19.000
[Guest 2]: And so if your starting point is this is a good thing, we need to encourage it and we need to find ways to accommodate for it.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:29.000
[Guest 2]: I think you will come down a path that looks very similar to New York and Barcelona and all of these places as opposed to the mentality mostly here, which is urbanization is a terrible thing.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:34.000
[Guest 2]: And by the way, every single person who thinks urbanization is a terrible thing lives in a city.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:35.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, absolutely.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And this is like I just did a couple of episodes with Ranguha on Gandhi and this was one of Gandhi's tropes that villages are, you know, India should be a country of villages and blah, blah, blah.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:53.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me in India, therefore, per se, how have cities tended to evolve and how has the planning mindset tended to sort of.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:58.000
[Guest 2]: So I'll let the planning question be answered by Pritika, but just the Gandhi question.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:16.000
[Guest 2]: Keep in mind the fact that he was taken to task by none other than Dr. Ambedkar, who actually pointed out to Gandhi the hypocrisy of someone who grew up in a city and lived in London and Johannesburg and Pretoria and Mumbai, making the case for how great villages are.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
[Guest 2]: That's typically the way the case is made.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:21.000
[Guest 2]: And Ambedkar's point was I actually grew up in a village.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:28.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Guha made the point in his biography that at one point where he was in London, he'd gone for his education, Gandhi, not Guha.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And Gandhi wrote an essay idealizing the pastoralists, the Indian pastoralists and all that.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And there was a very funny throwaway line about Brahmin bathes every day, Vaishya bathes once in two days and a pastoralist bathes once a week.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:41.000
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, they are great.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:45.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, they're healthy, they've got good bodies and they eat healthy food and breathe clean air.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And Guha points out that until this point in his life, he had probably never spoken to a villager in his life, you know, grew up in Porbandar, Rajkot, urban centers, goes to London and so on and so forth.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.000
[Amit Varma]: But that's a digression.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:10.000
[Guest 2]: But just to just to continue that digression for a second, I mean, keep in mind, Gandhi is heavily influenced by Henry David Thoreau, who's also talking about the same thing in the United States, the pastoralist movement and so on and so forth.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:21.000
[Guest 2]: But yes, I mean, I think every country goes through this phase of the romance of, you know, this is the classic, you know, the grass is greener on the other side, except in this case, I don't even know what the other side is.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:24.000
[Guest 2]: It's idealized and sitting in my head.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:28.000
[Amit Varma]: No, and people demonize cities so much and yet everybody wants to come here.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:34.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the very fact of urban migration tells you that a lot of the tropes that exist in our discourse are mistaken.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:45.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, people say population is a bad thing, India's problem is population, but all human movement is a movement to places with greater population density because as Julian Simon said, people are the ultimate resource.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And a similar point I make about inequality when I talk about inequality and poverty being very different things.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And all of human movement is towards, especially by the poor, is towards places with greater inequality, which is cities.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:01.000
[Guest 2]: And one of the things that, so I always think of cities as poverty digesters, right?

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.000
[Guest 2]: Because it actually allows you to escape poverty.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:04.000
[Guest 2]: Exactly.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:05.000
[Guest 2]: Right?

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:10.000
[Guest 2]: To which one of the sort of non-intuitive things that is always mentioned is, but then why are cities poor?

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:15.000
[Guest 2]: Cities are poor precisely because there's more poor people coming in to get out of poverty.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:16.000
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
[Guest 2]: So you're, that's what's actually going on.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:28.000
[Guest 2]: But if you actually, I mean, no one's actually, from as far as I can tell, no one's actually done serious longitudinal research tracking people across time to see if they got wealthier.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:33.000
[Guest 2]: But I think anecdotally, you'll see it everywhere you look, which is people have escaped poverty by just moving to cities.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I just say revealed preferences say everything.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.000
[Amit Varma]: You don't need data beyond that.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:42.000
[Amit Varma]: People just keep coming to cities and however much you decry slums, the people there are living there voluntarily.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:43.000
[Amit Varma]: There is a reason for that.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:48.000
[Guest 2]: Yes. And slums, again, you know, people make the mistake of equating slums with poverty.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.000
[Guest 2]: Slums are the consequence of bad real estate policy.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:54.000
[Guest 2]: And that may be a good segue for Pritika to answer your previous question.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's get back to that.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.000
[Unknown]: Have you forgotten my question?

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
[Unknown]: No, even I've forgotten it.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:00.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:10.000
[Amit Varma]: So my question basically was that, you know, while abroad there might have been this tendency for cities to be drawn along grids and planning and so on and so forth.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:17.000
[Amit Varma]: In India, I would imagine, especially looking at the state of our cities today, there's possibly been a little more anarchic than that, not in a bad way.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And how have Indian cities like, you know, Bombay, Delhi, whichever, traditionally evolved and how have planners intersected with that in terms of the mindset that they bring to what cities are?

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:41.000
[Guest 1]: I think a broad way to answer that question is, you know, even if we had better planned cities at the core, I think an inability to allow our cities to scale has been the problem.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:44.000
[Guest 1]: So, you know, we just talked about slums.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:52.000
[Guest 1]: I mean, slums are really failing to appreciate the fact that people are moving to the city and what you need then is more formal sector housing.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:59.000
[Guest 1]: So what a lot of Indian cities have done, or industrial policy did to some extent, was to say, look, you know, cities are growing.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
[Guest 1]: You know, we can't control population.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:04.000
[Guest 1]: We aren't able to provide amenities.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:12.000
[Guest 1]: And so there was incentives for manufacturing to, or mandates rather, for manufacturing and universities to locate outside of cities.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:24.000
[Guest 1]: I think there's constantly, and this comes from the master planning approach, right, that we will spread development more evenly across the region, or we will not allow for densification.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:28.000
[Guest 1]: And so, you know, mandate that things spread out more evenly.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.000
[Guest 2]: I'm not answering this question.

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:38.000
[Guest 2]: I think one other way to sort of think about it is, I mean, and this may be controversial, but urban planners tend to think of cities the way they would think of buildings, right?

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:42.000
[Guest 2]: Because a lot of them sort of come from this sort of architectural background.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:45.000
[Guest 2]: A building is a static concept, right?

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:46.000
[Guest 2]: You can plan a building.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:54.000
[Guest 2]: To then apply that mindset to something that is fundamentally a dynamic, ever evolving organism, right?

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.000
[Guest 2]: And then to apply these principles, I think it's just a very bad idea.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:00.000
[Guest 2]: And I think that's typically what has happened.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:10.000
[Guest 2]: If you look across the universe of planners who understand the underlying market economics of why people move and live in cities, I'd say that's a very, very small number in the world.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
[Guest 2]: That's a very small number in India.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:13.000
[Amit Varma]: It would be minuscule.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:19.000
[Amit Varma]: And would it be fair to say, to carry that analogy forward, that a building is made of bricks, but cities are made of people.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:21.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, it's very dynamic.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:24.000
[Amit Varma]: You can't plan, I mean, the same way you can't plan or control markets.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:33.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, in general, you know, I mean, and you and I probably agree on this, I mean, I don't know is a very useful starting point on all of these exercises.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:39.000
[Guest 2]: And so exercising some level of humility to say, I don't really know where this goes.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:44.000
[Guest 2]: And then, you know, so let that humility be your sort of binding constraint.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:47.000
[Guest 2]: And then with that, now do what you need to do.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:52.000
[Amit Varma]: You're a guy who interacts with politicians and bureaucrats and you're talking to me about humility.

